he historical CESM2 simulation driven with ERA5 wind background. c, Differences of winter precipitation trends between CESM2 nudged simulation and the ERA5 reanalysis. Dot stippling represents significance at the 0.05 level (P-value < 0.05). d–f, Magnitude of linear trends from the ERA5 reanalysis and the CESM2 nudged ERA5 simulation with anthropogenic forcing ending in 2022 as a function of start year over NEU (d), SEU (e) and ENA (f).Extended Data Fig. 5 Decomposition of precipitation trends into internal, forced, dynamic and thermodynamic components.a–c, Density distributions of total, total internal and total anthropogenic forced precipitation trends. d–f, Density distributions of full dynamic (d), internal dynamic (e) and anthropogenic forced dynamic (f) precipitation trends. g–i, Density distributions of full thermodynamic (g), internal thermodynamic (h) and anthropogenic forced thermodynamic (i) precipitation trends. Density curve estimation and decomposition methods are detailed in Methods. The decomposition is based on CESM2-LE using statistical learning models and nudged climate model experiments. Because ERA5 reanalysis reflects a single realization, ideal separation into internal, forced, dynamic and thermodynamic components is not possible. For comparison, polygon-based density plots are used to represent ERA5-derived results in panels a, d and g.Extended Data Fig. 6 CMIP6-based decomposition of precipitation trends.a–c, Density distributions of total, total internal and total anthropogenic forced precipitation trends. d–f, Density distributions of total dynamic (d), internal dynamic (e) and anthropogenic forced dynamic (f) precipitation trends. g–i, Density distributions of total thermodynamic (g), internal thermodynamic (h) and anthropogenic forced thermodynamic (i) precipitation trends. The detailed density curves estimation and decomposition can be found in Methods. This decomposition is based on the CMIP6 ensemble using statistical learning models.